Date: 0/0/1777
Source: Voyage Round the World
Author: FORSTER
Vol / Page: 1/129
Edition:
Quote: reference to American beer ... the resemblance it bore to the fir tribe ... soon convinced us that it was fitter to serve the purposes of [130] the American spruce-tree, and that a palatable and wholesome liquor might be brewed from it, as a kind of substitute for spruce-beer. ... The spruce of New-Zeeland is a very beautiful tree, and conspicuous on account of its pendant branches ... <i>Ibid.</i> I/143 But the constant supply of fresh fish ... together with the spruce-beer and the myrtle-tea, contributed to keep us healthy ... even in this damp climate.
